itis","Malaria"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAccording to the World Health Organization, \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculosis\u003C/strong\u003E is the leading cause of death from a single infectious agent worldwide, causing approximately 1.6 million deaths annually. While \u003Cstrong\u003Ediarrhoeal diseases\u003C/strong\u003E remain a significant cause of mortality, particularly in children under five years, they cause fewer deaths overall. \u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E mortality has decreased significantly with improved access to antiretroviral therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E causes approximately 1.1 million deaths annually from both acute infection and complications. \u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E causes over 600,000 deaths annually, primarily in sub-Saharan Africa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute lower respiratory infections, particularly pneumonia, are the leading infectious cause of death across all age groups globally.","Lower respiratory infections cause over 2.6 million deaths annually worldwide.","Tuberculosis remains the deadliest single infectious disease, causing approximately 1.6 million deaths annually."],"references":["World Health Organisation. Tuberculosis resurges as top infectious disease killer. 2024. WHO. Available from: https://www.who.int/news/item/29-10-2024-tuberculosis-resurges-as-top-infectious-disease-killer","Pan American Health Organisation. Tuberculosis resurges as top infectious disease killer. WHO. 2024. Available from: Tuberculosis resurges as top infectious disease killer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14848"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/4